      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_23130_1826_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1826-xx-xx"/>1826</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                            My dear Miss Edgeworth<!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                        </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>My correspondence has been interrupted first by my
                    wandrings in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#FR">France</placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> &amp; next by a such melancholy incident the
                    death of my Nephew <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuxlC1">Colonel Huxley</persName> of the 71<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> whom I expected from
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Halifax_ENK">Halifax</placeName> to pass the Christmas holidays with us but of whom his wife &amp;
                    child have been deprived by the sudden &amp; shocking accident of his death
                    on the eve of departing from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Halifax_ENK">Halifax</placeName>. He was a brave soldier regular in
                    all his habits attached to his <del/>wife &amp; family and maintaining <choice>
                  <orig>com-
                        plete</orig>
                  <reg>complete</reg>
               </choice>independence on very limited Means. Their <unclear/> had of
                    late enlarged by a bequest to my sister in law from her late brother
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MacCD1">David Macculloch</persName> to the amount sum of £10,000 which established the
                    whole family in complete independence - and now when they expected
                    him to come over here and he had to <unclear>taken</unclear> his passage - when I had seen
                    his wife at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Clullin-Cheltenham_ENK">Clullin Cheltenham</placeName> in all the happiness of expectation comes
                    this fatal intelligence. The distress of of course has been immense and
                    I own I have been my self much shocked at the loss of a brave soldier
                    which all admitted him to be and at the same time a much gentle
                    obliging friendly man in this unexpected and such disastrous
                    manner. It has really put me out of sorts in the body as well as
                    the mind or perhaps the extraordinary open state of the state
                    has given me an unusual stance of the stomach complaints &amp;
                    rheumatics that are going about. Yesterday on arriving here I had
                    to be lifted out of the carriage so compleatly were my joints
                    disabled by the rheumatism. But the hot bath &amp; <del>opost</del> opodeledic
                    have put a little verve in Harlequin <unclear/> day I would have
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_23130_1826_page02.jpg"/>   
                    however pressure to scale <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KevaS1">Sam Kevans</persName> bed for a fortnight to come Walter
                    is going about the house wearing the little harness in memoriam
                    because none of the cavalry <unclear>immediately</unclear> on the run for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#PO">Portugal</placeName>
               <unclear>believes</unclear>
                    to the 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. but he has some [underline]hopes[/underline] from the newspapers as your countryman
                    said when for a Crtt be <unclear>awarded</unclear> to be carried up to the Nursery of a
                    of <del>sto</del>house &amp; felt his <unclear>braces totter </unclear> under him when he reached the summit
                    which gave him <hi rend="underline">hopes</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Cruett has give to Bran Luath and the dogs of other dogs; the distemper
                    so fatal to the breed cut her off although <del>she</del>
               <add>he</add> had been vaccinated care
                    fully which is the best prevention I know but it seems not a certain
                    one. You must therefore wait till Next spring when we will try to
                    supply the plan of the exhausted Cruett. It is rather a hard choice for
                    I picked him out of three which we brought up &amp; the other two are
                    with <persName ref="Personography.xml#DundR1">Dundas of Arniston</persName> the other with very very active friend
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HughX1">Mrs Hughes</persName> hers both <unclear>got well over</unclear> the distemper.</p>
            <closer>
                    <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
                </closer>
